        <item>
			<title>Ron Silliman on Experimental Language Poetry</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://nigelbeale.libsyn.com/ron-silliman-on-experimental-language-poetry]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p><img src="http://www.poetryfoundation.org/uploads/authors/ron-silliman/448x/ron-silliman.jpg" alt="" height="185" width="283" /><span style="font-size: xx-small;">Jeff Hurwitz</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: large;">This from the Poetry Foundation: "An influential figure in contemporary poetics, <a href="http://www.poetryfoundation.org/bio/ron-silliman">Ron Silliman </a>became associated with the West Coast literary movement known as &ldquo;Language poetry&rdquo; in the 1960s and &lsquo;70s. He edited <em>In the American Tree </em>(1986), which remains the primary Language poetry anthology, as well as penned one of the movement&rsquo;s defining critical texts, <em>The New Sentence</em> (1987). Silliman&rsquo;s prolific publishing career includes over thirty books of poetry, critical work, collaborations and anthologies. He has long championed experimental or &ldquo;post-avant&rdquo; poetics, most recently through <em>Silliman&rsquo;s Blog,</em> a weblog he started in 2002."</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: large;">I met recently with <a href="http://www.ronsilliman.blogspot.ca/">Ron</a> at the Ottawa International Airport to talk about Language poetry. Among other things we discuss the 'Bardic I"; diagnosis of the self; examining viewpoint; the concept of clarity in writing; literary effects; passion through form; Raid killing bugs dead; manipulation of the reader; the artificiality of literary devices and preset responses. <a href="http://www.poetryfoundation.org/bio/louis-zukofsky">Louis Zukofsky</a>. Received rather than earned wisdom. Shakespeare as a great font of creative invention. Bing Crosby as the Jimi Hendricks of the microphone. <a href="http://www.steveroggenbuck.com/p/helvetica-poems.html">Steve Roggenback. </a>The 'God help us' response. Unquestioned ideology. Ambiguity. Self check-out lanes. Common denominators.&nbsp; Helen Vendler's irrelevancy. Poets' dishonest criticism. And the importance of reading series.</span></p>
<p></p>]]></description>
            <guid isPermaLink="false"><![CDATA[e635d5aa8eab371b77b7f75e46e91f1d]]></guid>
            <media:thumbnail url="http://assets.libsyn.com/item/1935725" />
            <pubDate>Fri, 04 May 2012 14:25:00 +0000</pubDate>
            <itunes:explicit>no</itunes:explicit>
			<itunes:keywords>new,language,poetry,experimental,ron,helen,sentence,louis,silliman,zackovsky,vendler</itunes:keywords>

	<itunes:subtitle><![CDATA[Jeff Hurwitz
This from the Poetry Foundation: "An influential figure in contemporary poetics, Ron Silliman became associated with the West Coast literary movement known as &ldquo;Language poetry&rdquo; in the 1960s and &lsquo;70s. He edited In the American Tree (1986), which remains the primary Language poetry anthology, as well as penned one of the movement&rsquo;s defining critical texts, The New Sentence (1987). Silliman&rsquo;s prolific publishing career includes over thirty books of poetry, critical work, collaborations and anthologies. He has long championed experimental or &ldquo;post-avant&rdquo; poetics, most recently through Silliman&rsquo;s Blog, a weblog he started in 2002."
I met recently with Ron at the Ottawa International Airport to talk about Language poetry. Among other things we discuss the 'Bardic I"; diagnosis of the self; examining viewpoint; the concept of clarity in writing; literary effects; passion through form; Raid killing bugs dead; manipulation of the reader; the artificiality of literary devices and preset responses. Louis Zukofsky. Received rather than earned wisdom. Shakespeare as a great font of creative invention. Bing Crosby as the Jimi Hendricks of the microphone. Steve Roggenback. The 'God help us' response. Unquestioned ideology. Ambiguity. Self check-out lanes. Common denominators.&nbsp; Helen Vendler's irrelevancy. Poets' dishonest criticism. And the importance of reading series.
]]></itunes:subtitle>



