        <item>
			<title>John Randle on The Whittington Press</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://nigelbeale.libsyn.com/interview-with-john-randle-on-the-whittington-press]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nigelbeale/5824435030/" title="John Randle at Gregynog  by Literary Tourist, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2251/5824435030_7abc75ea00.jpg" alt="John Randle at Gregynog " width="279" height="187" /></a></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;">Born in the mind of John Randle at the age of 14 when he first entered his school's press room, the <a href="http://www.whittingtonpress.com/">Whittington Press</a> started life in a disused gardener&rsquo;s cottage in 1971.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;"><a title="The Whittington Press by Nigel Beale, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nigelbeale/5373043162/"><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5086/5373043162_10c8117cd3.jpg" alt="The Whittington Press" width="280" height="212" /></a></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;">&nbsp;Its first book, Richard Kennedy&rsquo;s <em>A Boy at the Hogarth Press</em>, was printed on weekends during 1971-1972 on an 1848 Columbian. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;">Matrix - &nbsp;the Randle&rsquo;s revered annual publication on fine press printing - started out as a planned slim volume of some thirty two pages saddle stitched into stiff covers; the objective was for it to serve as &ldquo; a means of seeing in print a few short pieces which would not in themselves justify the production of individual titles, but which together might make a worthwhile publication.&rdquo; Matrix 1 grew to seventy two pages, and had to be square backed. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;"><a title="The Whittington Press by Nigel Beale, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nigelbeale/5372444271/"><img src="http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5246/5372444271_343ca211a3.jpg" alt="The Whittington Press" width="280" height="317" /></a></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;">With it the Randle&rsquo;s created an environment in which &ldquo;author, artist and printer, punchcutter and typecaster &ldquo;can work separately and together to both nurture and explore each others&rsquo;skills. The revered annual provides an important platform for typographical dialog among and between fine press aficionados on both sides of the Atlantic Ocean.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;">I met John Randle recently in his repurposed gardener&rsquo;s cottage to talk about his Press, his calling, and his thoughts about the practice of fine press printing.&nbsp; Please listen to our conversation here: </span></p>]]></description>
            <guid isPermaLink="false"><![CDATA[2ca9ec86e2ceb9e15da01f617c24905b]]></guid>
            <media:thumbnail url="http://assets.libsyn.com/item/1457988" />
            <pubDate>Thu, 20 Jan 2011 01:59:00 +0000</pubDate>
            <itunes:explicit>no</itunes:explicit>
			<itunes:keywords>john,press,matrix,fine,randle,whittington</itunes:keywords>

	<itunes:subtitle><![CDATA[
Born in the mind of John Randle at the age of 14 when he first entered his school's press room, the Whittington Press started life in a disused gardener&rsquo;s cottage in 1971.

&nbsp;Its first book, Richard Kennedy&rsquo;s A Boy at the Hogarth Press, was printed on weekends during 1971-1972 on an 1848 Columbian. 
Matrix - &nbsp;the Randle&rsquo;s revered annual publication on fine press printing - started out as a planned slim volume of some thirty two pages saddle stitched into stiff covers; the objective was for it to serve as &ldquo; a means of seeing in print a few short pieces which would not in themselves justify the production of individual titles, but which together might make a worthwhile publication.&rdquo; Matrix 1 grew to seventy two pages, and had to be square backed. &nbsp;

With it the Randle&rsquo;s created an environment in which &ldquo;author, artist and printer, punchcutter and typecaster &ldquo;can work separately and together to both nurture and explore each others&rsquo;skills. The revered annual provides an important platform for typographical dialog among and between fine press aficionados on both sides of the Atlantic Ocean.
I met John Randle recently in his repurposed gardener&rsquo;s cottage to talk about his Press, his calling, and his thoughts about the practice of fine press printing.&nbsp; Please listen to our conversation here: ]]></itunes:subtitle>



