			<title>Leslie Morris on New Directions </title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://traffic.libsyn.com/nigelbeale/Leslie_Morris.mp3]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<h2 id="post-6985"></h2>
<div class="entrytext">
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;" face="Times New Roman" size="4"><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/nigelbeale/4588530160/" title="IMG_0290 by Nigel Beale, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4064/4588530160_90884e72e9.jpg" alt="IMG_0290" width="278" height="370" /></a></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;" face="Times New Roman" size="4">Leslie Morris is Curator of Modern <a title="Books" href="http://literarytourist.com/2010/07/audio-interview-with-curator-leslie-morris-on-new-directions/bookstores">Books</a> and Manuscripts at <a href="http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/houghtonmodern/">Houghton Library, Harvard University </a>in Cambridge MA and an expert on the <a href="http://www.ndpublishing.com/home.html">New Directions publishing house</a>. I met with her recently to talk about publisher James &lsquo;Jay" Laughlin </span></p>
<blockquote>
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;" face="Times New Roman" size="4">"New Directions was founded in 1936, when James Laughlin (1914 &ndash; 1997), then a twenty-two-year-old Harvard sophomore, issued the first of the New Directions anthologies. "I asked Ezra Pound for &lsquo;career advice,&rsquo;" James Laughlin recalled. "He had been seeing my poems for months and had ruled them hopeless. He urged me to finish Harvard and then do &rsquo;something&rsquo; useful." </span></p>
</blockquote>
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;" face="Times New Roman" size="4">and the history of his venerable firm. Subjects covered include Ezra Pound, dust jacket designer Alvin Lustig, experimental poetry, works in translation&hellip;all of which are informed by an underlying desire to get at those books within this publisher&rsquo;s output that might most appeal to book collectors and book lovers generally.</span></p>
