			<title>David Staines on Northrop Frye and Evaluative Criticism</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://nigelbeale.libsyn.com/professor-david-staines-on-northrop-frye-and-evaluative-criticism]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;" face="Times New Roman" size="4"><img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4042/4392294684_39d6380fe6.jpg" alt="" width="281" height="363" /></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;" face="Times New Roman" size="4"><a href="http://www.english.uottawa.ca/faculty/dstaines.html"><strong>David Staines</strong></a> is a Canadian literary critic, university professor (English at the University of Ottawa), writer, and editor.&nbsp; He specializes in three literatures: medieval, Victorian and Canadian. He is editor of the scholarly <em>Journal of Canadian Poetry</em> (since 1986) and general editor of <a href="http://www.mcclelland.com/NCL/index.html">McClelland and Stewart&rsquo;s New Canadian Library</a> series (since 1988). His essay collections, include <em>The Canadian Imagination</em> (1977), a book that introduced Canadian literature and literary criticism to an American audience, plus studies on Morley Callaghan and Stephen Leacock.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;" face="Times New Roman" size="4">But it&rsquo;s not for any of this (save a defense of Callaghan in the face of <a href="http://nigelbeale.com/2009/05/14/on-negative-book-reviewing-audio-interview-with-john-metcalf/">John Metcalf&rsquo;s condemnations</a>) that I sought&nbsp; Prof. Staines&rsquo; company. Rather it&rsquo;s because he co-edited <a href="http://www.utppublishing.com/product.php?productid=430&amp;cat=0&amp;page=1"><em>Northrop Frye on Canada</em> (University of Toronto, 2001)</a>. Frye, Canada&rsquo;s most celebrated literary theorist, a man many hold responsible for the dearth of evaluative analysis in Canadian criticism; a man whose thoughts and person Staines knows (and knew) very well; is the reason we met. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;" face="Times New Roman" size="4">Please listen here to a conversation that reveals the author of <em>Fearful Symmetry </em>and <em>The Anatomy of Criticism </em>as a surprisingly self contradictory critic; speaks to the remarkable talent of Alice Munro and Canada&rsquo;s current stock of strong fiction writers; outlines criteria for acceptance into the <em>New Canadian Library</em>; and identifies some of the best Canadian novels.</span></p>]]></description>
            <guid isPermaLink="false"><![CDATA[http://nigelbeale.libsyn.com/index.php?post_id=627651#]]></guid>
            <media:thumbnail url="http://assets.libsyn.com/item/1197555" />
            <pubDate>Mon, 28 Jun 2010 15:54:00 +0000</pubDate>
			<itunes:keywords>john,new,literature,david,canadian,library,frye,northrop,metcalf,staines</itunes:keywords>

	<itunes:subtitle><![CDATA[
David Staines is a Canadian literary critic, university professor (English at the University of Ottawa), writer, and editor.&nbsp; He specializes in three literatures: medieval, Victorian and Canadian. He is editor of the scholarly Journal of Canadian Poetry (since 1986) and general editor of McClelland and Stewart&rsquo;s New Canadian Library series (since 1988). His essay collections, include The Canadian Imagination (1977), a book that introduced Canadian literature and literary criticism to an American audience, plus studies on Morley Callaghan and Stephen Leacock.
But it&rsquo;s not for any of this (save a defense of Callaghan in the face of John Metcalf&rsquo;s condemnations) that I sought&nbsp; Prof. Staines&rsquo; company. Rather it&rsquo;s because he co-edited Northrop Frye on Canada (University of Toronto, 2001). Frye, Canada&rsquo;s most celebrated literary theorist, a man many hold responsible for the dearth of evaluative analysis in Canadian criticism; a man whose thoughts and person Staines knows (and knew) very well; is the reason we met. 
Please listen here to a conversation that reveals the author of Fearful Symmetry and The Anatomy of Criticism as a surprisingly self contradictory critic; speaks to the remarkable talent of Alice Munro and Canada&rsquo;s current stock of strong fiction writers; outlines criteria for acceptance into the New Canadian Library; and identifies some of the best Canadian novels.]]></itunes:subtitle>



