			<title>Carmine Starnino: On Canadian Poems and Poets </title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://traffic.libsyn.com/nigelbeale/Carmine_Starnino_800306_01.mp3]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<div class="entrytext">
<p><img src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_FvwCbuu4pBM/Sggj_n6JINI/AAAAAAAAAbQ/0Y3GX7dzY3c/s1600/Starnino,%2BCarmine%2B-%2Bnew%2Bphoto.jpg" alt="" height="325" width="278" /><span style="font-size: xx-small;" size="1"><a href="http://gaspereaupress.blogspot.com/2009/05/carmine-starnino-in-montreal.html">Photo: Gaspereau Press.</a></span></p>
<p align="left"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;" face="Times New Roman" size="4">"Good reviewing," writes <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carmine_Starnino">Carmine Starnino</a> in the not-to-be-missed introduction to his<em> <a href="http://porcupinesquill.ca/bookinfo3.php?index=157">A Lover&rsquo;s Quarrel Essays and Reviews</a></em>, "- reviewing that believes in literary failure &ndash; is invaluable because by calling one poem good and another less good, and adducing clear reasons for those claims, it offers one writerly interpretation of a particular achievement, and invites the reader to sypathetically tag along; his or her senses momentarily borrowing the reviewer&rsquo;s responses." <br /> </span></p>
<p align="left"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: medium;" face="Times New Roman" size="4">We met recently in a somewhat echoey corner of the National Gallery in Ottawa to hold <a href="http://www.gaspereau.com/155447051x.shtml">Starnino&rsquo;s most recent collection of poetry, <em>This Way Out</em>,</a> up to scrutiny, naming names. Which of his poems are good, which bad; who are the best and worst contemporary Canadian poets. Listen here as we walk the walk of <em>A Lover&rsquo;s Quarrel:</em></span></p>
</div>]]></description>
            <guid isPermaLink="false"><![CDATA[733913cd04c7adfa08586ef6ea29fc70]]></guid>
            <media:thumbnail url="http://assets.libsyn.com/item/1197551" />
            <pubDate>Mon, 21 Jun 2010 12:56:00 +0000</pubDate>
			<itunes:keywords>canadian,poetry,criticism,carmine,starnino</itunes:keywords>

	<itunes:subtitle><![CDATA[
Photo: Gaspereau Press.
"Good reviewing," writes Carmine Starnino in the not-to-be-missed introduction to his A Lover&rsquo;s Quarrel Essays and Reviews, "- reviewing that believes in literary failure &ndash; is invaluable because by calling one poem good and another less good, and adducing clear reasons for those claims, it offers one writerly interpretation of a particular achievement, and invites the reader to sypathetically tag along; his or her senses momentarily borrowing the reviewer&rsquo;s responses."  
We met recently in a somewhat echoey corner of the National Gallery in Ottawa to hold Starnino&rsquo;s most recent collection of poetry, This Way Out, up to scrutiny, naming names. Which of his poems are good, which bad; who are the best and worst contemporary Canadian poets. Listen here as we walk the walk of A Lover&rsquo;s Quarrel:
]]></itunes:subtitle>



