			<title>Author Jane Urquhart: On Lucy Maud Montgomery</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://traffic.libsyn.com/nigelbeale/Jane_Urquhart_LMM_111207-185347_2.mp3]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2689/4050483772_c92770a680.jpg" alt="" width="277" height="324" /></p>
<div><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">Published in 1908, <em>Anne of Green Gables</em> is the first in a series of bestselling novels by Canadian author </span></span><a title="Lucy Maud Montgomery" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucy_Maud_Montgomery"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">Lucy Maud Montgomery</span></span></a><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">. Although often dark and complex, and at times racy, the &lsquo;Anne&rsquo; novels are today considered by most to be children&rsquo;s books. Inspired by similar girls&rsquo; stories of the time, and her own childhood experiences in rural </span></span><a title="Prince Edward Island" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prince_Edward_Island"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">Prince Edward Island</span></span></a><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">, Montgomery&rsquo;s writing has affected generations of women around the world, perhaps none more so than another Canadian, novelist</span></span><a href="http://www.extraordinarycanadians.com/authors/urquhart.html"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"> Jane Urquhart,</span></span></a><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"> </span></span><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">who has just written a biography of Lucy Maud as part of&nbsp; Penguin&rsquo;s </span></span></div>
