	<itunes:subtitle><![CDATA[
Published in 1908, Anne of Green Gables is the first in a series of bestselling novels by Canadian author Lucy Maud Montgomery. Although often dark and complex, and at times racy, the &lsquo;Anne&rsquo; novels are today considered by most to be children&rsquo;s books. Inspired by similar girls&rsquo; stories of the time, and her own childhood experiences in rural Prince Edward Island, Montgomery&rsquo;s writing has affected generations of women around the world, perhaps none more so than another Canadian, novelist Jane Urquhart, who has just written a biography of Lucy Maud as part of&nbsp; Penguin&rsquo;s 

Extraordinary Canadians series. We met recently to talk about the vast disconnect between the work and the woman; depression, lesbianism and gaiety; about place, truth and memory, narrative and culture, confidence and role models.&nbsp;
