			<title>Bookseller Don Lindgren on Collecting Cooking Books</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://traffic.libsyn.com/nigelbeale/Don_Lindgren__Rabelais_801219_01.mp3]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2627/3901270921_9e869545d9.jpg" alt="" width="277" height="369" /><br /> </span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">Researching &lsquo;literary&rsquo; Portland (Maine) before trekking down there, I came across mention of <a href="http://rabelaisbooks.blogspot.com/">Rabelais Book shop</a>.&nbsp; What an interesting concept it&rsquo;s built upon:&nbsp; the vertical integration of new titles on food, wine, gardening and farming, with rare out-of-print&nbsp; books. Patrons therefore inhabit several distinct categories:&nbsp;Book lovers and collectors from around the globe, food lovers and cooks from around the block. Situated in<strong> </strong>Portland&rsquo;s East End next door to </span></span><a href="http://hugos.net/"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">Hugo&rsquo;s</span></span></a><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"> (chef Rob Evans won the 2009 James Beard award for Best Chef Northeast) and within walking distance of half a dozen other great restaurants, including </span></span><a href="http://bresca.org/Site/Welcome.html"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">Bresca</span></span></a><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">, </span></span><a href="http://www.duckfat.com/"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">Duckfat</span></span></a><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"> and </span></span><a href="http://www.forestreet.biz/"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">Fore Street</span></span></a><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">, the store, in several short years, has become the go-to place for New England&rsquo;s foodies<strong>. </strong>Hosting author readings, art exhibits, film showings/dinners and&nbsp; Slow Food meetings, the shop is a jointly owned by Samantha Hoyt Lindgren, a former photo editor and pastry chef, and her husband Don, an antiquarian book dealer. I met with Don at Hugo&rsquo;s &ndash; we thought it would be quieter there than in the store &ndash; to talk food and books&hellip;listen for the names of titles you might want to start collecting here:</span></span></p>
<p><a href="http://nigelbeale.libsyn.com/rss" id="bodyLinks" target="_blank"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"><em>Subscribe to the Biblio File Podcast here</em></span></a></p>]]></description>
