Researching &lsquo;literary&rsquo; Portland (Maine) before trekking down there, I came across mention of Rabelais Book shop.&nbsp; What an interesting concept it&rsquo;s built upon:&nbsp; the vertical integration of new titles on food, wine, gardening and farming, with rare out-of-print&nbsp; books. Patrons therefore inhabit several distinct categories:&nbsp;Book lovers and collectors from around the globe, food lovers and cooks from around the block. Situated in Portland&rsquo;s East End next door to Hugo&rsquo;s (chef Rob Evans won the 2009 James Beard award for Best Chef Northeast) and within walking distance of half a dozen other great restaurants, including Bresca, Duckfat and Fore Street, the store, in several short years, has become the go-to place for New England&rsquo;s foodies. Hosting author readings, art exhibits, film showings/dinners and&nbsp; Slow Food meetings, the shop is a jointly owned by Samantha Hoyt Lindgren, a former photo editor and pastry chef, and her husband Don, an antiquarian book dealer. I met with Don at Hugo&rsquo;s &ndash; we thought it would be quieter there than in the store &ndash; to talk food and books&hellip;listen for the names of titles you might want to start collecting here:
