This from the incom&shy;par&shy;able Brit&shy;ish Council&rsquo;s con&shy;tem&shy;por&shy;ary writers web&shy;site:  
Born in South&shy;port in 1969, David Mitchell grew up in Mal&shy;vern, Worcester&shy;shire, study&shy;ing for a degree in Eng&shy;lish and Amer&shy;ican Lit&shy;er&shy;at&shy;ure fol&shy;lowed by an MAin Com&shy;par&shy;at&shy;ive Lit&shy;er&shy;at&shy;ure, at the Uni&shy;ver&shy;sity of Kent. He lived for a year in Sicily before mov&shy;ing to Hiroshima, Japan, where he taught Eng&shy;lish to tech&shy;nical stu&shy;dents for eight years, before return&shy;ing to England.
In his first novel, Ghostwrit&shy;ten (1999), nine nar&shy;rat&shy;ors in nine loc&shy;a&shy;tions across the globe tell inter&shy;lock&shy;ing stor&shy;ies. This novel won the Mail on Sunday/John Llewellyn Rhys Prize and was short&shy;l&shy;is&shy;ted for the Guard&shy;ian First Book&nbsp;Award.
His second novel, number9dream (2001), was short&shy;l&shy;is&shy;ted for the 2002 Man Booker Prize for fic&shy;tion. It is set in mod&shy;ern day Tokyo and tells the story of Eiji Miyake&rsquo;s search for his father.

&nbsp;
In 2003 David Mitchell was named by Granta magazine as one of twenty &lsquo;Best of Young Brit&shy;ish Nov&shy;el&shy;ists&rsquo;. In his third novel, Cloud Atlas (2004), a young Pacific islander wit&shy;nesses the night&shy;fall of sci&shy;ence and civil&shy;isa&shy;tion, while&nbsp;ques&shy;tions of his&shy;tory are explored in a series of seem&shy;ingly dis&shy;con&shy;nec&shy;ted nar&shy;rat&shy;ives.&nbsp;Cloud Atlas was short&shy;l&shy;is&shy;ted for the 2004 Man Booker Prize for Fiction.
&nbsp;
David Mitchell lives in Ire&shy;land. His latest novel is Black Swan Green (2006)
&nbsp;
We met recently in Toronto to talk about exper&shy;i&shy;ment&shy;a&shy;tion and real&shy;ism, plot, char&shy;ac&shy;ter and all that good stuff, but also about the great&shy;ness of John Cheever, high brow and pulp fic&shy;tion, good pot boil&shy;ers, the cos&shy;mos, cosmi, con&shy;nec&shy;tions, meld&shy;ing verbs, plat&shy;it&shy;ud&shy;in&shy;ous pro&shy;fundit&shy;ies, crit&shy;ics as platy&shy;pus taxi&shy;derm&shy;ists, poetry in prose, the ori&shy;gin&shy;al&shy;it&shy;ies of happy blun&shy;ders and cul&shy;tural jux&shy;ta&shy;pos&shy;i&shy;tions, Perec&rsquo;s W, mon&shy;key&shy;ing with struc&shy;ture, plan&shy;ning your funeral, eval&shy;u&shy;at&shy;ive cri&shy;ti&shy;cism and the delight&shy;ful exper&shy;i&shy;ence of read&shy;ing Chekhov&rsquo;s short stor&shy;ies.  
