			<title>Booksellers Joshua and Phyllis Heller on Artists' Books</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://nigelbeale.libsyn.com/booksellers-joshua-and-phyllis-heller]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p><img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2503/3712032880_2ca270a435.jpg" alt="" width="278" height="366" /></p>
<div id="refHTML" style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">What&rsquo;s the dif&shy;fer&shy;ence between a First Edi&shy;tion, a Fine Press Edi&shy;tion and an Artists&rsquo; Book? Joshua and Phyl&shy;lis Heller work with me to help define the bound&shy;ar&shy;ies.&nbsp;<br /> </span></span></div>
<div style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"><br /> </span></span></div>
<div style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">The two of them estab&shy;lished </span></span><a href="http://www.joshuahellerrarebooks.com/"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">Joshua Heller Rare Books, Inc</span></span></a><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">. in Wash&shy;ing&shy;ton <span class="caps">DC</span>, in 1985. The com&shy;pany spe&shy;cial&shy;izes in &ldquo;con&shy;tem&shy;por&shy;ary fine print&shy;ing and beau&shy;ti&shy;fully illus&shy;trated books, the Private Press Move&shy;ment, mod&shy;ern fine bind&shy;ings, and books about books. [Their] much admired cata&shy;logues, illus&shy;trated in full color, are dis&shy;trib&shy;uted to a national and inter&shy;na&shy;tional list of cli&shy;ents.&rdquo; <br /> </span></span></div>
<p style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">Joshua has lec&shy;tured widely in the United States and Canada on the art of the book. He helped organ&shy;ize the Art of the Con&shy;tem&shy;por&shy;ary Book Con&shy;fer&shy;ence at Ohio State Uni&shy;ver&shy;sity in 1991, and has: con&shy;trib&shy;uted art&shy;icles on the Private Press Move&shy;ment to journ&shy;als such as <em>Fine Print</em> and <em>Imprint</em>; and cur&shy;ated exhib&shy;i&shy;tions of South African botan&shy;ical artist Elise Bod&shy;ley, both for the Smith&shy;so&shy;nian Museum of Nat&shy;ural His&shy;tory and the Audu&shy;bon Soci&shy;ety; he also pro&shy;posed the first Wash&shy;ing&shy;ton Artists&rsquo; Book Fair &ndash; now a bien&shy;nial event; and organ&shy;ized the first ever exhib&shy;i&shy;tion of fine mod&shy;ern bind&shy;ings at the Corcoran Museum of Art in Wash&shy;ing&shy;ton <span class="caps">DC</span> in 2003.<br /> </span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;">I met the Hellers at their home in Wash&shy;ing&shy;ton, D.C. recently. Please listen here to our conversation</span></span></p>
