        <item>
			<title>Joseph Boyden on his Giller Prize winning novel Through Black Spruce</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://nigelbeale.libsyn.com/author-joseph-boyden-]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-size: small;"><img src="http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3152/2980841711_d237dc625f.jpg?v=0" alt="" height="373" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="280" align="bottom" border="0" /></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: medium;">Joseph Boyden has just won&nbsp; <a href="http://www.scotiabankgillerprize.ca/">The 2008 Giller Prize&nbsp; </a>for his novel <span style="font-style: italic;">Through Black Spruce.&nbsp; </span>We talk here about the novel, and the psychic distance Joseph requires to write novels about Northern Ontario and the Cree; the similarities between North and South, James Bay and New Orleans; snowmobiling over vast amounts of snow-covered bush, isolation in the wilderness; bridges between communities, oral culture, First Nation humour, respect for myths and legends, and soapboxes. Please excuse the abrupt ending!</span></p>
<div></div>
<p><span style="font-size: medium;">For more interviews and book reviews <a>www.nigelbeale.com</a> Copyright &copy; 2008 by Nigel Beale. www.nige</span>lbeale.com</p>]]></description>
            <guid isPermaLink="false"><![CDATA[http://nigelbeale.libsyn.com/index.php?post_id=402266#]]></guid>
            <media:thumbnail url="http://assets.libsyn.com/item/1197299" />
            <pubDate>Wed, 12 Nov 2008 04:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
			<itunes:keywords>black,interview,joseph,author,prize,through,boyden,spruce,giller</itunes:keywords>

	<itunes:subtitle><![CDATA[
Joseph Boyden has just won&nbsp; The 2008 Giller Prize&nbsp; for his novel Through Black Spruce.&nbsp; We talk here about the novel, and the psychic distance Joseph requires to write novels about Northern Ontario and the Cree; the similarities between North and South, James Bay and New Orleans; snowmobiling over vast amounts of snow-covered bush, isolation in the wilderness; bridges between communities, oral culture, First Nation humour, respect for myths and legends, and soapboxes. Please excuse the abrupt ending!

