        <item>
			<title>Rebecca Rosenblum on What Constitutes a Good Short Story (1): </title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://nigelbeale.libsyn.com/author-rebecca-rosenblum-on-what-constitutes-a-good-short-story-1-]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-size: small;"><img src="http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3027/2980785051_981a91baf7.jpg?v=0" alt="" vspace="0" width="275" align="baseline" border="0" height="332" hspace="0" /></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: medium;">This is part one of a series of interviews conducted with three acclaimed short storywriters: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rebecca_Rosenblum">Rebecca Rosenblum</a>, <a href="http://www.randomhouse.com/knopf/catalog/results2.pperl?authorid=79093">Nam Le</a>, and <a href="http://www.mcclelland.com/catalog/display.pperl?isbn=9780771030734">Anne Enright.</a> In each case we riff off those qualities which Flannery O&rsquo;Connor thought best constituted a good short story. <a href="http://nigelbeale.com/?p=1040">I&rsquo;ve listed some of them here. </a></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: medium;">We start with Rebecca Rosenblum, author of <a href="http://www.biblioasis.com/product_info.php?products_id=75">Once</a>, " a collection of sixteen stories portraying the constricted and confused lives of the rootless twenty-somethings &mdash; students, office techies, waitresses, warehouse labourers, street hustlers &mdash; who inhabit them. These are stories grounded in the all-too-real comedy and tragedy of jobs and friendships and romances, books and buses and bodies." This debut collection won The Metcalf Rooke Award. </span></p>
<p><strong><span style="font-size: small;">&nbsp;Please listen here: </span></strong></p>
<p>Copyright &copy; 2008 by Nigel Beale. www.nigelbeale.com</p>]]></description>
