            <pubDate>Sat, 01 Nov 2008 17:45:00 +0000</pubDate>
			<itunes:keywords>and,story,short,nam,anne,oconnor,rebecca,le,enright,flannery,rosenblum</itunes:keywords>

	<itunes:subtitle><![CDATA[
This is part one of a series of interviews conducted with three acclaimed short storywriters: Rebecca Rosenblum, Nam Le, and Anne Enright. In each case we riff off those qualities which Flannery O&rsquo;Connor thought best constituted a good short story. I&rsquo;ve listed some of them here. 
We start with Rebecca Rosenblum, author of Once, " a collection of sixteen stories portraying the constricted and confused lives of the rootless twenty-somethings &mdash; students, office techies, waitresses, warehouse labourers, street hustlers &mdash; who inhabit them. These are stories grounded in the all-too-real comedy and tragedy of jobs and friendships and romances, books and buses and bodies." This debut collection won The Metcalf Rooke Award. 
