        <item>
			<title>Author Elias Khoury </title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://nigelbeale.libsyn.com/author-elias-khoury-]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p>Elias Khoury is author of eleven novels including <em>Little Mountain</em> and <em>Gates of the City</em>. He is currently professor of Middle Eastern and Islamic studies at New York University, and editor in chief of the literary supplement of Beirut&rsquo;s daily newspaper, <em>An-Nahar</em>. We talk here, at the <a href="http://bluemetropolis.org/Festival">Blue Metropolis Montreal International Literary Festival</a>, about his latest novel in English <em>Gate of the Sun</em>, of how great literature speaks to what is human and how religion doesn&rsquo;t; of how telling stories helps us to overcome death, and how knowledge helps to overcome power; of keys, loss, hatred and love; of how important the right to story, memory and language is to the existence of a people; of the double tragedy of Palestine in 1948, the real one and the fact that the telling of this catastrophe has not been permitted; of how reading literature helps us discover ourselves and of how literature attempts to give meaning to the meaninglessness of life.</p>
<p>www.nigelbeale.com</p>]]></description>
